ates)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life==\nHudson was born in [[Franklin, Virginia]]; but has lived in the [[Charlotte]] area since 1975.  He graduated from [[Myers Park High School]] in 1990, and from the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]] in 1996, where he became a member of [[Kappa Alpha Order]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressman Richard Hudson|url=http://www.kappaalphaorder.org/2013/01/kas-in-public-service/hudson|publisher=Kappa Alpha Order|accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe is the president of Cabarrus Marketing Group, a small business consulting firm.\n\nActive in politics for many years, Hudson served as district director for 8th District Congressman [[Robin Hayes]] from 1999 to 2005.  At various times, he served on the staffs of Republicans [[Virginia Foxx]], [[John Carter (Texas)|John Carter]] and [[Mike Conaway]].  He also served as communications director for the North Carolina Republican Party.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\nHudson ran for Congress in North Carolina's 8th congressional district. He won the Republican primary runoff on July 17, 2012, with 64% of the vote against opponent [[Scott Keadle]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Hudson to take on Kissell in U.S. District 8|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/07/17/3388590/hudson-to-take-on-kissell-in-us.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=18 July 2012|author=David Perlmutt and Lukas Johnson}}</ref> and faced Democratic incumbent [[Larry Kissell]] in November.  The district had been made significantly more Republican in redistricting, losing most of its share of Charlotte and picking up several heavily Republican areas northeast of the city.\n\nRichard Hudson spoke at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] in [[Tampa, Florida]] on August 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Concord hopeful Hudson speaks role at Republican National Convention|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2012/08/28/3485275/concord-hopeful-hudson-speaks.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Charlotte Observer|date=28 August 2012|author=Franco Ordo\u00f1ez}}</ref>\n\nHudson defeated Kissell with 54 percent of the vote to Kissell's 46 percent and took office in January 2013.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit|Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training|Subcommittee on Higher Education and Workforce Training]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Management|Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Management]]\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]] (Chair)\n\n===Legislation sponsored===\n* [[Transportation Security Acquisition Reform Act (H.R. 2719; 113th Congress)]] - Hudson introduced this bill into the US House on July 18, 2013.<ref name=2719sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 2719 - Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th/house-bill/2719|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref> If passed, the bill would require the [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) to develop a comprehensive technology acquisition plan.<ref name=techreform1>{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=House to push tech reform at TSA|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/technology/191721-house-to-push-tech-reform-at-tsa|accessdate=4 December 2013|newspaper=The Hill|date=2 December 2013}}</ref> The [[Government Accountability Office]] and the [[Department of Homeland Security Office of Inspector General]] each found that the TSA's lack of a technology acquisition plan led to waste, excessive costs, and security failures.<ref name=\"techreform1\"/> This bill was written in response.\n* [[Gerardo Hernandez Airport Security Act of 2014 (H.R. 4802; 113th Congress)]] - Hudson introduced ths bill into the House on June 6, 2014.<ref name=4802sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4802 - Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4802|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> The bill is a reaction to lessons learned from the [[2013 Los Angeles International Airport shooting]].<ref name=LATweikel>{{cite news|last1=Weikel|first1=Dan|title=House passes bill to improve airport security in wake of LAX shooting|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-airport-security-bill-20140722-story.html|accessdate=23 July 2014|publisher=LA Times|date=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Press Accomplishments===\n*[[New Congressman Meets with Local Farmers (The Lexington Dispatch)]]-\"The freshman Republican congressman from Concord, who was recently appointed to the House Committee on Agriculture, made nine stops in the district from Monday through Wednesday. At each stop, his staff collected contact information from the farmers, who he said will serve as his informal agriculture advisory board.\u201d<ref name=\"The Lexington Dispatch\">{{cite news|last1=Hodges|first1=Vikki|title=New Congressman Meets with Local Farmers-Summary|url=http://www.the-dispatch.com/article/20130130/NEWS/130139993/0/search|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hudson Proposes Elimination of Estate Tax (Richmond County Daily Journal)]]- \u201cU.S. Representative Richard Hudson, from North Carolina\u2019s 8th Congressional, is looking to permanently eliminate the death tax, also known as the inheritance tax or the estate tax, that is imposed on the transfer of taxable estates of a deceased person.\u201d<ref name= \"Richmond County Daily Journal\">{{cite news|last1=Edington|first1=Laura|title=Hudson Proposes Elimination of Estate Tax|url=http://hudson.house.gov/in-the-news/hudson-proposes-elimination-of-estate-tax/#.U_IEj_ldVHo|publisher=Richmond County Daily Journal|date=8 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hudson talks jobs at Harrisburg Meeting (Concord Independent-Tribune)]]-\u201cJobs, jobs, jobs\u2019 are the main issues for 8th District Congressman Richard Hudson, who met with local business and government leaders at Harrisburg Town Hall Tuesday morning.\u201d<ref name=\"Concord Independent Tribune\">{{cite news|last1=Plemmons|first1=Mark|title=Hudson talks jobs at Harrisburg Meeting|url=http://m.independenttribune.com/news/hudson-talks-jobs-at-harrisburg-meeting/article_fb971a9a-6478-5307-868a-42e6a89f30cb.html?mode=jqm||publisher= Concord Independent-Tribune|date=2 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hudson\u2019s Bipartisan Efforts Are to be Applauded (Richmond County Daily Journal)]]- \u201cIn short, this is a great idea that should be broadened to include many other facets of the federal government. But therein lies the beauty of Hudson\u2019s goal \u2014 the freshman Republican knew not to reach for the stars. Instead, he decided to reach for a piece of the atmosphere and he\u2019s now \u201cthis close\u201d to getting it.\u201d<ref name=\"Richmond County Daily Journal\">{{cite web|title=Hudson\u2019s Bipartisan Efforts Are to be Applauded|url= http://hudson.house.gov/in-the-news/hudsons-bipartisan-efforts-are-to-be-applauded/#.U_IEF_ldVHo|publisher=Richmond County Daily Journal|date=31 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n*[[Hudson Named Most Conservative Member of Congress (National Journal)]]<ref name=:National Journal\">{{cite web|title=15Most Conservative Representatives|url= http://www.nationaljournal.com/pictures-video/the-15-most-conservative-representatives-20140206|publisher=National Journal|date=6 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n*[[Rep Hudson talks unemployment benefits, minimum wage, jobs (Salisbury Post)]]- \u201cU.S. Rep. Richard Hudson said he is standing on his original campaign goal of being a congressman who reaches across the aisle while continuing to stand on his own principles.\u201d<ref name=\"Salisbury Post\">{{cite news|last1=Holt|first1=Jim|title=Rep Hudson talks unemployment benefits, minimum wage, jobs|url=http://www.salisburypost.com/article/20140221/SP01/140229951/0/SEARCH&slId=9|publisher=Salisbury Post|date=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n*[[Inside the House GOP Leadership Shake-Up (Politico)]]- \u201cThere was Rep. Patrick McHenry, the shrewd North Carolina Republican. Roskam, who was elected with McCarthy in the Democrat-heavy year of 2006, was there, too. Rep. Richard Hudson (R-N.C.) \u2014 a rising star in the Capitol\u2014showed up with his wife, Renee, a GOP fundraising consultant.\u201d<ref name=Politico>{{cite web|title=Rep Hudson talks unemployment benefits, minimum wage, jobs|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/06/inside-the-house-gop-leadership-shake-up-108103.html|publisher=Politico|date=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n*[[Another EEOC Embarrassment (Wall Street Journal)]]- \u201cLast week, North Carolina Rep. Richard Hudson introduced a bill that would force the EEOC to be more transparent about its operations and \"notify Congress within 14 days when a court has ordered sanctions against EEOC.\" Womble Carlyle's experience shows why that's an excellent idea.\u201d<ref name=\"Wall Street Journal\">{{cite news |last1=Kissel|first1=Mary |title= Another EEOC Embarrassment|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/political-diary-another-eeoc-embarrassment-1404222707|publisher=Wall Street Journal|date=1 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n*[[Thought bipartisanship gone way of dinosaur? (High Point Enterprise)]]- \u201cFirst-term U.S. Rep. Richard Hudson, R-8th, showed Tuesday that bipartisanship at the nation\u2019s capital isn\u2019t quite dead yet..The conservative congressman who represents parts of Davidson County joined Democratic President Barack Obama as the president signed a workforce retraining reform bill that Hudson supported. The event marked the first time that Hudson attended a bill-signing ceremony at the White House.\u201d<ref name=\"High Point Enterprise\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Paul|title=Thought bipartisanship gone way of dinosaur?|url= http://www.hpe.com/news/davidsoncounty/x143264372/Thought-bipartisanship-gone-way-of-dinosaur|publisher=High Point Enterprise|date=23 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|North Carolina}}\n*[http://hudson.house.gov/ Congressman Richard Hudson] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.richardhudsonforcongress.com/ Richard Hudson for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Richard_Hudson_%5BR-8%5D|Richard Hudson}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = H001067 | ballot = Richard_Hudson  | nndb = | votesmart = 136448 | govtrack = 412550 | opencong = 412550 | rollcall = 44602 | politifact = | fec = H2NC08185 | opensecrets = N00033630 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = | ontheissues = NC/Richard_Hudson.htm | congress = richard-hudson/2140 | worldcat = | cspan = 79622 | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = 22ad1ec6-4bbc-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Larry Kissell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from North Carolina|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[North Carolina's 8th congressional district]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steven Horsford]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United S